Windows Subsystem For Linux (WSL) Guide
What is WSL?
The Windows Subsystem for Linux (WSL) is a feature of Windows that allows developers to run a GNU/Linux environment—including most command-line tools, utilities, and applications—directly on Windows, unmodified, without the overhead of a traditional virtual machine or dual-boot setup.

How to Install a Linux Distro
To install the default distribution (usually Ubuntu), open PowerShell or Command Prompt as Administrator and run:
wsl --install

To see other available distributions, use:
wsl --list --online

How to Install a Desktop Environment (DE)
Since WSL is terminal-based by default, you can use Tasksel to quickly install a full desktop interface (like XFCE, GNOME, or KDE).

Update your package list:

Bash
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y
Install Tasksel:

Bash
sudo apt install tasksel
Run Tasksel to choose your DE:

Bash
sudo tasksel
Space: Select/Deselect an item.

Tab: Move to the "OK" button.

Enter: Confirm and start the installation.

Accessing the Desktop via Remote Desktop (RDP)
1. Install the Remote Desktop Server
You need a way to "beam" the desktop from Linux to Windows. xrdp is the most common tool for this.

Bash
sudo apt install xrdp
sudo systemctl enable xrdp
sudo systemctl start xrdp
2. Get your WSL IP Address
Find the internal IP address assigned to your Linux instance:

Bash
ip -br a
Note: Look for the address under eth0 (usually starts with 172.x.x.x).

3. Connect from Windows
Open the Remote Desktop Connection app on Windows.

Paste the IP address you found in the previous step.

Click Connect, enter your Linux username and password, and enjoy your Linux Desktop!
